"1400–Deceased","1404–Female":"1404–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1404":"1404","ABT    1400":"about 1400","1446":"1446","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","Abt. 1400":"about 1400","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","ABT    1370":"about 1370","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","ABT    1404":"about 1404","of,Hope,Flintshire,Wales":"Hope, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Brynbuga,Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of, Rhuddallt, Rhiwabon, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruabon, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Hendreforfudd,Corwen,Merionethshire,Wales":"Hendreforfudd, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Jenkin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is derived from the medieval given name <i>Jankin</i>. This was a pet form of the boy's name   Jan  , with the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. The modern given name is popular in Wales, where the surnames <i>Jenkin</i> and <i>Jenkins</i> are common."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jenkin ap Gruffudd was born about 1370, in Hendreforfudd, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Ieuan ap Gruffudd, was 32 and his mother, Gwellian verch Ieuan ab Gruffudd Goch ap Philip ap Iowerth ap Maredudd ap Madog Danwr, was 27. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Angharad ferch Deio."},"et":{"ABT    1370–":"umbes 1370–Surnud","1370